Life, Moods, Productivity, and Macbook Usage

Helen Mary Labao-Barrameda

11/18/2018

Executive Summary

The bullet journal method of logging everyday habits combined with a granular analysis of my personal activity in my Macbook tries to get a more data-driven idea of what affects my productivity in using my Macbook.

This exploratory report mainly aims to shed light on some questions such as: where does my time go? Am I productive despite my regular struggle with depression? How can I improve my life with better time and energy management?

Exploratory Data Analyses

Dependencies

Install library dependencies first to ensure that code will run seamlessly: devtools, ggplot2, dplyr, reshape2, treemapify, ggplotify, ggpubr, and tidyr.

The Data

It involves 400+ hours on the Macbook (137,000+ rows) analyzed within a 3-month period (FinalExamData_Barrameda_raw.csv). I also encoded a portion of my bullet journal entries that documents my mood, basic nutrition, etc. (BulletJournalData.csv) Each day in the bullet journal has a Self-Care and Mood score.

# load the datasets

Super #WorkisLife, Apparently!

More than half of my computer life (311/437 hours) is devoted to my 2 homebased IT and data projects with Cascadeo Corporation and MonetizeMore. No wonder I feel so tired and they dont want me to quit my job! =D

Almost 10 hours is wasted updating, waiting, and installing things. That System76 laptop may be a justifiable wish for my next birthday, after all.

Its Not a Very Manic Monday!

The Timing app I used captures 1 log entry for each key stroke I make on my Mac. I analyzed the frequency of keystrokes per weekday to see when are my most hyper days. Why is my Sunday computer activity like this?!? (Well, its Sunday now) On the 10% of actual computer leisure, I identified my most favored apps.

So, which habit correlates with my productivity and distractibility?

During a subset of the period of observation, I managed to track my personal well-being through my bullet journal for around 3 weeks.

Self-Care vs Mood

The 3-week data is simply not enough to correlate mood to self-caring.
